<DOC><DOCNO> AP881114-0068 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1232EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Strike     11-14 0136</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Italy-Strike,0141</SECOND><HEAD>Most Flights Canceled At North Italian Airports</HEAD><DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   National and international flights werecanceled at airports in northern Italy because of a 12-hour strikeby air traffic controllers Monday, but Tuesday's schedulednationwide strike was called off.   The strike forced the cancellation of flights to and from Milan,Turin, Genoa, Venice and Pisa.   ``Only flights to the Italian islands were unaffected by thewalkout,'' said a spokesman for Milan's Linate airport. ``All otherflights were canceled.''   The unions called off Tuesday's scheduled 13-hour nationwidestrike after reaching an accord with management.   The agreement calls for more flexible work schedules andpromotion of 500 controllers to a higher pay category.   The controllers agreed to suspend any labor unrest through Jan.16 pending final acceptance of the agreement by the two sides.</TEXT></DOC>